bonus/
├── .gitignore              # excludes credentials.txt
├── scripts/
│   ├── install-prereqs.sh  # installs Docker, k3d, kubectl, helm
│   └── setup.sh            # main script: cluster + ArgoCD + GitLab
└── confs/
    ├── gitlab-values.yaml  # Helm configuration for minimal GitLab
    ├── argocd-app.yaml     # Argo CD Application (points to local GitLab)
    └── manifests/
        ├── deployment.yaml # wil-playground v1 (pushed to GitLab repo)
        └── service.yaml    # ClusterIP service for the app

The critical new concept: Kubernetes internal DNS
This is the most important thing in the bonus. In Part 3, Argo CD reached GitHub over the public internet.
In the bonus, Argo CD reaches GitLab using Kubernetes internal DNS:
http://gitlab-webservice-default.gitlab.svc.cluster.local:8181.
This works because every Kubernetes Service automatically gets a DNS entry following the pattern:
 <service-name>.<namespace>.svc.cluster.local.
 No port-forwarding, no external network — it's direct pod-to-pod communication within the cluster.


 How to run it on your Droplet

SSH into your Droplet
Copy the bonus/ folder to your project
Run bash bonus/scripts/install-prereqs.sh (installs Helm — the only new tool)
Run bash bonus/scripts/setup.sh (takes 10-15 minutes, mostly waiting for GitLab)


------------------------------------------------------- check if the setup is done -----------------------------------------------
# 1. Verify all three namespaces exist
kubectl get ns

# 2. Check pods in each namespace
kubectl get pods -n gitlab
kubectl get pods -n argocd
kubectl get pods -n dev

# 3. Check the Argo CD application status
kubectl get applications -n argocd

# 4. Test the app responds with v1
kubectl port-forward svc/wil-playground-svc -n dev 8888:8888 &
in case the port is already in use, do the following:
# Find what's using port 8888
sudo lsof -i :8888

# Or kill all port-forwards
pkill -f "port-forward"

# Then retry OR use a different local port 8889 for example

kubectl port-forward svc/wil-playground-svc -n dev 8889:8888 &
curl http://localhost:8889


------------------------------------------------------- check if the setup is done -----------------------------------------------

script to test the sqirch from v1 to v2 

# Port-forward GitLab
kubectl port-forward svc/gitlab-webservice-default -n gitlab 8181:8181 &

# Clone the repo from local GitLab
git clone http://root:glpat-Ub1o2hmYmH93NNwywxuF8W86MQp1OjEH.01.0w1x0vwkm@localhost:8181/root/arabiai-iot.git
cd arabiai-iot

# Change v1 to v2
sed -i 's/wil42\/playground:v1/wil42\/playground:v2/g' manifests/deployment.yaml

# Push to local GitLab
git add . && git commit -m "Update to v2" && git push

# Wait ~30 seconds for Argo CD to sync, then verify
sleep 30
curl http://localhost:8888


-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# if port-forward for the app got killed when the pod restarted during the v2 deployment.
# Kill any stale port-forwards
pkill -f "port-forward.*8889"

# Wait for the new pod to be ready
kubectl wait --for=condition=Ready pods -l app=wil-playground -n dev --timeout=60s

# Re-establish port-forward
kubectl port-forward svc/wil-playground-svc -n dev 8889:8888 &
sleep 3

# if it doesn't work
sudo lsof -i :8181
# Note the PID, then:
kill -9 <PID>

# Retry
kubectl port-forward svc/gitlab-webservice-default -n gitlab 8181:8181 &

# Test
curl http://localhost:8889
curl http://localhost:8181